0823?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
If you get as fired up reading this essay as I did writing it, you can simp=
ly go build radar satellite clusters to map the Earth in 3D by joining Arra=
y Labs:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Tuesday! It=E2=80=99s fall in New York City, the Eagles looked great =
on Monday Night Football, and I get to bring you a deep dive that=E2=80=99s=
 been melting my brain for weeks.=20
If I=E2=80=99ve spoken with you over the past few weeks, chances are I=E2=
=80=99ve told you about Array Labs. It was designed for me. A deeply Hard S=
tartup, riding exponential technology curves, to build distributed systems =
for space, to enable businesses on Earth, with a strategy as thoughtful as =
its hardware.
Nothing makes me happier than banging my head against a complex company lik=
e Array for weeks to understand it well enough to share it with all of you.=
 This is a longer essay that I=E2=80=99ve written in a while, because fully=
 appreciating what Array is trying to do requires some knowledge of the ear=
th observation market, how satellites work, how radars work, business strat=
egy, the self-driving car market, and more.=20
This is a Sponsored Deep Dive. I=E2=80=99ve always said that I=E2=80=99d on=
ly write them on companies I=E2=80=99d want to invest in =E2=80=94 and I ho=
pe to invest in Array Labs when they raise next =E2=80=94 and as Not Boring=
 Capital=E2=80=99s thesis has tightened to Hard Startups that can bend the =
world=E2=80=99s trajectory upwards, so has the deep dive bar. Array clears =
that bar by hundreds of kilometers. You can read more about how I choose wh=
ich companies to do deep dives on, and how I write them here [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/3da1d5d3-8923-45c1-905b-9046ca7ec780?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
So throw on some appropriate music=E2=80=A6=20
And let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Array Labs: 3D Mapping Earth from Space
A real-time, 3D map of the world is the holy grail of earth observation (EO=
).=C2=A0
Possessing such a map would enable new applications and technologies, from =
self-driving cars to augmented reality. It would improve climate monitoring=
, disaster response, construction management, resource management, and even=
 urban planning.=C2=A0
Access to a real-time global 3D map would confer significant strategic and =
economic advantages to whoever possesses it. The US government has spent un=
told billions of dollars over decades for more accurate and timely informat=
ion about the state of the world. Real estate developers, insurers, and ene=
rgy producers could turn the data from that map into dollars.=C2=A0
But holy grails are, by definition, difficult to obtain. The map doesn=E2=
=80=99t currently exist, and it=E2=80=99s not for lack of trying.=C2=A0
Array Labs [ https://substack.com/redirect/40dec0ea-6455-4f3b-848c-69ec9315=
0823?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] t=
hinks that now is the time to build it. And its founder, Andrew Peterson, t=
hinks he knows how.=C2=A0
The main thing you need is Very High Resolution Imagery (VHR) of gigantic s=
waths of Earth, freshly collected daily, to start, and more frequently over=
 time. There are a few ways, theoretically, you could collect the data.=C2=
=A0
You could send out a fleet of LiDAR-equipped self-driving cars, with humans=
 behind the wheel. That=E2=80=99s how Autonomous Vehicle (AV) companies do =
it today, one city at a time. But it=E2=80=99s too expensive and impractica=
l to cover the globe. At $20 per mile, it would cost over $1 trillion to ma=
p the Earth=E2=80=99s surface, even assuming cars could drive everywhere.=
=C2=A0
You might fly LiDAR-toting airplanes across the globe. When people want VHR=
 of specific areas today, that=E2=80=99s what they do. At around $500 per s=
quare kilometer (apologies for the mixed units, but we=E2=80=99re going wit=
h industry standards), a single US collection would be $5 billion. A global=
 collection would run you a cool quarter-trillion, assuming you can access =
all of the world=E2=80=99s airspace without getting shot down. Closer, but =
still not good enough.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s go even higher, from ground to planes to satellites. Satellit=
es rarely get shot down. They scan the entire globe, airspace be damned. On=
ce in orbit, they keep flying around and around and around at very high spe=
eds. And they=E2=80=99re way cheaper: at current retail pricing of around $=
50/sq. km, it would only cost you $150 million to cover the US, or $7.7 bil=
lion to cover the whole Earth.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re getting warmer, but there are still two main problems with th=
is approach:=C2=A0
Resolution. Today, the resolution from even the best 3D satellite collectio=
ns is still 100x worse than airplanes. You couldn=E2=80=99t guide self-driv=
ing cars with these maps.=C2=A0
Coverage Cost. Getting coverage by sending up enough high-resolution satell=
ites to capture the whole Earth would be too expensive to pencil out.
For a number of reasons we=E2=80=99ll get into, you can=E2=80=99t simply sc=
ale up current earth observation satellites to larger and larger sizes. The=
y get exponentially less efficient as you scale them, and assuming you work=
ed all of that out, a satellite big enough to provide the resolution and co=
verage you=E2=80=99d need would be way, way too big to send up on a rocket.=
=C2=A0
If you wanted to make the antenna really big =E2=80=93 like 50 kilometers i=
n diameter big =E2=80=93 it would be impossible with anything close to our =
modern capabilities. Such an antenna would be 1,000x taller and 5,000x wide=
r than SpaceX=E2=80=99s Starship. It would be 60x taller than the Burj Khal=
ifa. It would have 5.82x the diameter of CERN=E2=80=99s Large Hadron Collid=
er.=C2=A0
I tried to make an image to scale but it doesn=E2=80=99t come close to fitt=
ing on the screen. So let=E2=80=99s try a metaphor. If Starship were the si=
ze of a soda can, this 50 km diameter satellite antenna would be the size o=
f the island of Manhattan.=C2=A0
But a diameter that size is useful, because it helps increase vertical reso=
lution, a key piece if you want a true 3D map instead of a stack of high-re=
solution 2D pictures.=C2=A0
But having something that behaves like an enormous imaging satellite, or ev=
en just a giant radar antenna, would be really useful...=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a way to do that, but it=E2=80=99s kind of crazy.=C2=A0
What if instead, you kept the radar imaging satellites very small, but sent=
 dozens of them up there in a big ring?=C2=A0
When you do that, what you end up with is something that behaves like an ab=
solutely enormous antenna =E2=80=93 an antenna 30 miles wide =E2=80=93 that=
 improves exponentially.=C2=A0
Instead of a monolithic antenna that gets exponentially less efficient with=
 scale, you end up with a distributed system that gets more and more effici=
ent with every satellite you add. Each satellite has its own solar panels, =
providing plenty of power. Each one is small and stackable enough that the =
whole cluster fits on a single port on an ESPA ring, snuggling in amongst a=
ll of the other satellites on the next SpaceX rideshare mission. Pointing t=
hem at the target is as easy as adjusting a small cubesat, like directing a=
 ballet with dozens of prima ballerinas.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThen, pretty soon,=E2=80=9D Andrew explains, =E2=80=9CYou've got t=
he most efficient image collection system that ever existed in the history =
of mankind.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s what Array Labs is building, the crazy way: the most efficie=
nt image collection system that ever existed in the history of mankind. Its=
 mission is to create a daily-refreshed, high res 3D map of Earth.=C2=A0
To be sure, Andrew=E2=80=99s idea for Array Labs is crazy in a lot of ways.=
=C2=A0
For one, the Air Force Research Lab tried to use radar to make a 3D map of =
the Earth back in the early 2000s with a program called TechSat-21. Working=
 with DARPA, they designed the system to demonstrate formation-flying of ra=
dar satellites that would work together and operate as a single =E2=80=9Cvi=
rtual satellite.=E2=80=9D It was an idea ahead of its time, sadly, and the =
program was scrapped due to significant cost overruns.=C2=A0
For another, earth observation isn=E2=80=99t necessarily the rising star of=
 the space economy these days. There are already a bunch of EO satellites o=
rbiting our Blue Marble. Incumbents and upstarts alike, companies like Maxa=
r, Planet, and Blacksky, have a lot of capacity in orbit. A workable busine=
ss model has been harder to come by. Planet and Blacksky are both trading n=
ear all-time lows after coming public via a SPAC in 2021.=C2=A0
When Ryan Duffy and Mo Islam wrote a piece on The Space Economy [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/49aaed5e-630e-4f6b-bab3-10c4bacdb94c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for Not Boring last yea=
r, they weren=E2=80=99t particularly bullish on the EO market, which was wh=
y I was surprised when Duffy called me a couple of months ago to tell me ab=
out a company I absolutely had to meet =E2=80=A6 in EO.=C2=A0
He=E2=80=99d gotten bullish =E2=80=93 he was doing consulting work for them=
, and asked to take his pay in equity instead of cash =E2=80=93 but after f=
ive years at media startups writing newsletters about emerging tech, he tol=
d me that he was planning on doing his own thing for the foreseeable future=
=2E So I was doubly surprised when, on=20=
our next call, Duffy told me that he w=
as giving up the consulting life early to join Array Labs full-time as Head=
 of Commercial BD.=C2=A0
After he introduced me to Andrew, I understood why.=C2=A0
Array Labs has many of the characteristics I love to see in a startup. It=
=E2=80=99s ambitious and just the right kind of crazy. It=E2=80=99s reanima=
ting an idea that didn=E2=80=99t work before but might now thanks to expone=
ntial technology curves [ https://substack.com/redirect/7721aa88-41bd-4585-=
8e9c-809e3044ce9a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]. It=E2=80=99s turning something traditionally monolithic into s=
omething distributed. It=E2=80=99s using technological innovation to unlock=
 business model innovation, and executing against a clear strategy [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/ab443a2f-2cca-43bb-894e-23b1ca5e9bd0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] while it=E2=80=99s s=
till in its uncertainty period [ https://substack.com/redirect/1d02143a-cb3=
f-4e2f-ae31-a41d96b2bb84?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. And, if it works, it will enable new businesses to be b=
uilt that aren=E2=80=99t possible today.=C2=A0
In short, Array Labs both has its own powerful answer to the question, =E2=
=80=9CWhy now?=E2=80=9D and the rare opportunity to serve as other companie=
s=E2=80=99 answer.=C2=A0
But taking advantage of a powerful =E2=80=9CWhy now?=E2=80=9D means that it=
=E2=80=99s also very early. Array Labs plans to launch four demonstration s=
atellites next year and two more orbital pathfinder missions in 2025, befor=
e sending up its first full cluster in 2026. Risks abound.=C2=A0
That makes it a particularly fun time to write about the company. This essa=
y is a time capsule from before Array Labs becomes obvious. It=E2=80=99s a =
Not Boring thesis paper of sorts, and the thesis is this: a company with a =
near-perfect why now (and the right team to capture it) and a strategy to m=
atch the moment can both disrupt and grow an established industry while ena=
bling new ones.=C2=A0
To lay it out, we=E2=80=99ll need to cover a lot of ground in one pass:=C2=
=A0
Earth Observation: The 600km View
The Engineering Magic of SAR
How to Make the Most Efficient Image Collection System Ever
Intersecting Exponentials
Array Labs=E2=80=99 Strategy
Enabling New Markets
Risks
Mapping the Path to Mapping the World
Put on your spacesuit. Let=E2=80=99s launch into orbit to get a better view=
 of the industry.
Earth Observation: The 600km View
A couple of weeks ago, I wrote [ https://substack.com/redirect/a60ead95-22c=
c-40cb-bb40-237957674691?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CAny technology that is sufficiently valuable i=
n its ideal state will eventually reach that ideal state.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The earth observation market is sufficiently valuable, even in its current =
state. In 2022, estimates put the market size around $7 billion and growing=
 at roughly 10% annually. This is likely a fairly significant underestimate=
, as the US and other governments spend billions of dollars on highly class=
ified programs.=C2=A0
But the earth observation market isn=E2=80=99t close to its ideal state. In=
 its ideal state, earth observation would produce real-time, high-resolutio=
n, global coverage, easily consumable by the naked eye or machine learning =
models, accessible to anyone for their specific needs.=C2=A0
AV companies would ingest point clouds that turn into real-time maps, alert=
ing cars of changes in traffic conditions, construction projects, or closed=
 roads.=C2=A0
The Department of Defense would have real-time visibility into the movement=
 of enemy resources, no matter the weather or time of day.=C2=A0
Environmental groups would be able to track planetary indicators by the min=
ute.=C2=A0
Augmented Reality (AR) companies would design experiences that interact wit=
h the real world in real-time.=C2=A0
Foundation model companies, always hungry for more data to scale performanc=
e, could train their models on 3D and HD continental-level scans of the wor=
ld.=C2=A0
If the data was good and cheap enough, entrepreneurs would certainly dream =
up uses that I can=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
In its ideal state, earth observation will expand humanity=E2=80=99s abilit=
y to understand, respond to, and shape events on a global scale.=C2=A0
And we=E2=80=99re getting closer. Over the past century, we=E2=80=99ve made=
 significantly more progress towards that ideal state than we did in all of=
 the millennia of human history before it.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s much more where this came from. For history on mapmaking an=
d earth observation, a SAR primer, a peek into how Array plans to build the=
 most efficient image collection system in the history of mankind, the curv=
es it=E2=80=99s riding, its strategy, some risks, and where it=E2=80=99s he=
ading=E2=80=A6=20
(Click the button or the title up top to head over to Not Boring)
Here=E2=80=99s a little teaser:
Thanks to Dan for editing, and to Andrew and Duffy for teaching me the ins =
and outs of SAR and letting me tell the Array Labs story!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox with a We=
ekly Dose on Friday. Go get it this week.=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy

